✅ PROJECT NAME:

EV Vehicle Charge Demand Forecasting (Simplified Student Version)

🔧 STEP-BY-STEP IMPLEMENTATION:

🧩 STEP 1: Setup Your Environment

Open terminal (or notebook) and run:

bash

📁 STEP 2: Prepare Your Dataset

✅ Download and Use the Same Dataset

  • Visit the GitHub repo link

  • Save it in a local data/ folder

🧠 STEP 3: Build a Simple Prediction Model (student-style)

Create a Python file or Jupyter Notebook with the following simplified student-style code:

python
# ev_model.py
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
import joblib

# Load Data
df = pd.read_csv("data/ev_data.csv")

# Drop missing values
df.dropna(inplace=True)

# Select Features and Target
X = df[['Month', 'Temperature', 'EV_Registered']]
y = df['Charging_Demand']

# Train Model
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X, y)

# Save the model
joblib.dump(model, 'model/ev_model.pkl')

📝 Modification made:

  • Reduced features to three for simplicity

  • Dropped nulls instead of complex cleaning

  • Used only LinearRegression

🌐 STEP 4: Create Streamlit App (Modified version)

Create a new file app.py:

python
# app.py
import streamlit as st
import pandas as pd
import joblib

# Load Model
model = joblib.load("model/ev_model.pkl")

# Title
st.title("EV Charging Demand Forecasting")

# Input Widgets
month = st.number_input("Enter Month (1-12):", min_value=1, max_value=12)
temp = st.slider("Average Temperature (°C):", -10, 50, 25)
ev_reg = st.number_input("Number of EVs Registered:", min_value=0)

# Predict
if st.button("Predict Charging Demand"):
    input_data = pd.DataFrame([[month, temp, ev_reg]], columns=['Month', 'Temperature', 'EV_Registered'])
    prediction = model.predict(input_data)
    st.success(f"Predicted Charging Demand: {round(prediction[0], 2)} units")

📝 Modification made:

  • Replaced dropdowns with sliders and numeric input for simplicity

  • Single output prediction with less code

🔷 STEP 2: Build and Train Model in Notebook

🔹 Full code for notebook (ev_model_training.ipynb):

python
# 1. Import required libraries
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
import joblib

# 2. Load the dataset
df = pd.read_csv("ev_data.csv")

# 3. Clean the data (simple dropna)
df.dropna(inplace=True)

# 4. Select features and target
X = df[['Month', 'Temperature', 'EV_Registered']]
y = df['Charging_Demand']

# 5. Train the model
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X, y)

# 6. Test prediction
sample = pd.DataFrame([[6, 30, 1200]], columns=['Month', 'Temperature', 'EV_Registered'])
prediction = model.predict(sample)
print("Predicted charging demand:", round(prediction[0], 2))

# 7. Save the model
joblib.dump(model, "ev_model.pkl")

🔷 STEP 3: Create the Streamlit Web App

🔹 Create a file named app.py locally and paste this code:

python
import streamlit as st
import pandas as pd
import joblib

# Load trained model
model = joblib.load("model/ev_model.pkl")

st.title("EV Charging Demand Prediction App")

# Input from user
month = st.number_input("Month (1-12):", min_value=1, max_value=12)
temp = st.slider("Average Temperature (°C):", -10, 50, 25)
ev_count = st.number_input("Number of EVs Registered:", min_value=0)

if st.button("Predict Charging Demand"):
    input_df = pd.DataFrame([[month, temp, ev_count]], columns=['Month', 'Temperature', 'EV_Registered'])
    prediction = model.predict(input_df)
    st.success(f"Predicted EV Charging Demand: {round(prediction[0], 2)} units")

✅ Final Working Section (from loading to training):

python
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
import joblib

# Step 1: Load data
df = pd.read_csv("ev_data.csv")

# Step 2: Clean missing values
df.dropna(inplace=True)

# ✅ Step 3: Fix comma-separated numbers
cols_to_fix = ['EV_Registered', 'Charging_Demand']
for col in cols_to_fix:
    df[col] = df[col].astype(str).str.replace(',', '')  # remove commas
    df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col])

# Step 4: Select features and target
X = df[['Month', 'Temperature', 'EV_Registered']]
y = df['Charging_Demand']

# Step 5: Train model
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X, y)

# Step 6: Save model
joblib.dump(model, "ev_model.pkl")

from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
import joblib

# Step 1: Load data
df = pd.read_csv("ev_data.csv")

# Step 2: Clean column names (remove extra spaces)
df.columns = df.columns.str.strip()

# Step 3: Drop missing values
df.dropna(inplace=True)

# Step 4: Fix comma-separated strings
cols_to_fix = ['EV Registered', 'Charging Demand']
for col in cols_to_fix:
    df[col] = df[col].astype(str).str.replace(',', '')
    df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col])

# Step 5: Prepare features
X = df[['Month', 'Temperature', 'EV Registered']]
y = df['Charging Demand']

# Step 6: Train model
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X, y)

# Step 7: Save model
joblib.dump(model, "ev_model.pkl")

✅ ✅ FULL JUPYTER NOTEBOOK CODE — ev_model_training.ipynb

python
# ✅ Step 1: Import Libraries
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
import joblib

# ✅ Step 2: Download Dataset (only if not uploaded manually)
!wget https://raw.githubusercontent.com/RGS-AI/AICTE_Internships/main/2025/July_2025/EV_Vehicle_Charge_Demand/data/ev_data.csv

# ✅ Step 3: Load Dataset
df = pd.read_csv("ev_data.csv")

# ✅ Step 4: Clean Column Names (remove extra spaces)
df.columns = df.columns.str.strip()

# ✅ Step 5: Drop missing/null values
df.dropna(inplace=True)

# ✅ Step 6: Convert comma-containing strings to numbers
cols_to_fix = ['EV Registered', 'Charging Demand']
for col in cols_to_fix:
    df[col] = df[col].astype(str).str.replace(',', '')  # Remove commas
    df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col])  # Convert to numeric

# ✅ Step 7: Define Features (X) and Target (y)
X = df[['Month', 'Temperature', 'EV Registered']]
y = df['Charging Demand']

# ✅ Step 8: Train the Model
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X, y)

# ✅ Step 9: Make a Sample Prediction
sample_input = pd.DataFrame([[6, 30, 1500]], columns=['Month', 'Temperature', 'EV Registered'])
predicted_demand = model.predict(sample_input)
print("Predicted EV Charging Demand:", round(predicted_demand[0], 2), "units")

# ✅ Step 10: Save the Trained Model to a File
joblib.dump(model, "ev_model.pkl")

✅ FULL PROJECT GUIDE (Student Version)

Project: EV Charging Demand Forecasting
Goal: Predict electric vehicle (EV) demand using a regression model and visualize trends.

✅ Step 1: Preprocess the Data

🔹 Clean and prepare the data

python
import pandas as pd

# Clean column names
df.columns = df.columns.str.strip()

# Convert 'Date' to datetime
df['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Date'])

# Remove commas and convert vehicle columns to numeric
vehicle_columns = [
    'Battery Electric Vehicles (BEVs)',
    'Plug-In Hybrid Electric Vehicles (PHEVs)',
    'Electric Vehicle (EV) Total',
    'Non-Electric Vehicle Total',
    'Total Vehicles',
    'Percent Electric Vehicles'
]

for col in vehicle_columns:
    df[col] = df[col].astype(str).str.replace(',', '').astype(float)

# Check if all is clean
df.info()
df.head()

✅ Step 2: Feature Engineering

We’ll extract the month and year from the Date for trend analysis.

python
df['Year'] = df['Date'].dt.year
df['Month'] = df['Date'].dt.month

We’ll aggregate EV totals by month:

python
monthly_ev = df.groupby(['Year', 'Month'])['Electric Vehicle (EV) Total'].sum().reset_index()
monthly_ev['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(monthly_ev[['Year', 'Month']].assign(DAY=1))
monthly_ev = monthly_ev.sort_values('Date')

✅ Step 3: Build a Machine Learning Model (Linear Regression)

🔹 Create features (X) and target (y)

python
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
import numpy as np

monthly_ev['Month_Number'] = np.arange(len(monthly_ev))
X = monthly_ev[['Month_Number']]
y = monthly_ev['Electric Vehicle (EV) Total']

# Train the model
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X, y)

✅ Step 4: Make Predictions

python
monthly_ev['Predicted_EV_Demand'] = model.predict(X)

✅ Step 5: Plot the Results

python
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.plot(monthly_ev['Date'], monthly_ev['Electric Vehicle (EV) Total'], label='Actual')
plt.plot(monthly_ev['Date'], monthly_ev['Predicted_EV_Demand'], label='Predicted', linestyle='--')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('EV Registrations')
plt.title('EV Demand Forecast')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

✅ Step 6: Save the Model

python
import pickle

with open('ev_model.pkl', 'wb') as f:
    pickle.dump(model, f)

✅ Step 7: Convert to Streamlit App (Optional)

You can turn this into a Streamlit dashboard later with this in app.py:

python
import streamlit as st
import pandas as pd
import pickle

st.title("EV Charging Demand Forecast")

model = pickle.load(open("ev_model.pkl", "rb"))
st.write("Model loaded successfully.")

# Prediction UI
months = st.slider("How many months into the future?", 1, 24, 6)
future_X = pd.DataFrame({'Month_Number': [monthly_ev['Month_Number'].max() + i for i in range(1, months + 1)]})
future_preds = model.predict(future_X)

st.write("### Predicted EV Registrations for next", months, "months")
st.line_chart(future_preds)

Perfect! Here's a simple, student-friendly app.py file for your EV Vehicle Charging Demand Forecasting project using Streamlit:

✅ app.py (Full Code)

python
import streamlit as st
import pandas as pd
import pickle

# Set up the page
st.set_page_config(page_title="EV Charging Demand Forecast", layout="centered")

# Title of the app
st.title("🔋 EV Charging Demand Forecasting")

# Load the trained model
model = pickle.load(open("ev_model.pkl", "rb"))

# Upload CSV file
uploaded_file = st.file_uploader("Upload your EV data file (CSV format)", type=["csv"])

if uploaded_file is not None:
    # Read uploaded CSV
    data = pd.read_csv(uploaded_file)

    # Show uploaded data
    st.subheader("📄 Uploaded Data")
    st.write(data.head())

    # Clean numeric columns (remove commas)
    for col in ['Battery Electric Vehicles (BEVs)', 'Plug-In Hybrid Electric Vehicles (PHEVs)']:
        data[col] = data[col].astype(str).str.replace(',', '', regex=True).astype(float)

    # Prepare input features
    X = data[['Battery Electric Vehicles (BEVs)', 'Plug-In Hybrid Electric Vehicles (PHEVs)']]

    # Make predictions
    predictions = model.predict(X)

    # Show predictions
    st.subheader("📊 Predicted EV Demand")
    data['Predicted EV Demand'] = predictions
    st.write(data[['County', 'State', 'Predicted EV Demand']])

    # Downloadable CSV
    st.download_button("Download Predictions as CSV", data.to_csv(index=False), "ev_predictions.csv", "text/csv")

else:
    st.info("Please upload a CSV file to begin.")

📌 How to Use This File:

    • ev_model.pkl exists

    • You’ll upload CSV files via UI (like ev_data.csv)

  2. Run the app (locally):

🧠 If You Lost It or Want to Copy-Paste It

Here is the exact app.py code again (you can create a new file and paste it):

python
import streamlit as st
import pandas as pd
import pickle

st.set_page_config(page_title="EV Charging Demand Forecast", layout="centered")
st.title("🔋 EV Charging Demand Forecasting")

model = pickle.load(open("ev_model.pkl", "rb"))

uploaded_file = st.file_uploader("Upload your EV data file (CSV format)", type=["csv"])

if uploaded_file is not None:
    data = pd.read_csv(uploaded_file)
    st.subheader("📄 Uploaded Data")
    st.write(data.head())

    for col in ['Battery Electric Vehicles (BEVs)', 'Plug-In Hybrid Electric Vehicles (PHEVs)']:
        data[col] = data[col].astype(str).str.replace(',', '', regex=True).astype(float)

    X = data[['Battery Electric Vehicles (BEVs)', 'Plug-In Hybrid Electric Vehicles (PHEVs)']]
    predictions = model.predict(X)
    data['Predicted EV Demand'] = predictions

    st.subheader("📊 Predicted EV Demand")
    st.write(data[['County', 'State', 'Predicted EV Demand']])

    st.download_button("Download Predictions as CSV", data.to_csv(index=False), "ev_predictions.csv", "text/csv")
else:
    st.info("Please upload a CSV file to begin.")

✅ Step-by-Step: Generate app.py Inside Your Notebook

🔹 Paste and run this cell in your notebook:

python
app_code = '''
import streamlit as st
import pandas as pd
import pickle

st.set_page_config(page_title="EV Charging Demand Forecast", layout="centered")
st.title("🔋 EV Charging Demand Forecasting")

model = pickle.load(open("ev_model.pkl", "rb"))

uploaded_file = st.file_uploader("Upload your EV data file (CSV format)", type=["csv"])

if uploaded_file is not None:
    data = pd.read_csv(uploaded_file)
    st.subheader("📄 Uploaded Data")
    st.write(data.head())

    for col in ['Battery Electric Vehicles (BEVs)', 'Plug-In Hybrid Electric Vehicles (PHEVs)']:
        data[col] = data[col].astype(str).str.replace(',', '', regex=True).astype(float)

    X = data[['Battery Electric Vehicles (BEVs)', 'Plug-In Hybrid Electric Vehicles (PHEVs)']]
    predictions = model.predict(X)
    data['Predicted EV Demand'] = predictions

    st.subheader("📊 Predicted EV Demand")
    st.write(data[['County', 'State', 'Predicted EV Demand']])

    st.download_button("Download Predictions as CSV", data.to_csv(index=False), "ev_predictions.csv", "text/csv")
else:
    st.info("Please upload a CSV file to begin.")
'''

with open("app.py", "w") as file:
    file.write(app_code)

print("✅ app.py file created successfully!")
